  "prompt": "When and how did WWI start and end?",
  "response": "World War I began on July 28, 1914, and ended on November 11, 1918. \n\n### Start of WWI:\n- **Assassination of Archduke Ferdinand**: The immediate catalyst for the war was the assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria and his wife, Sophie, on June 28, 1914, in Sarajevo by Gavrilo Princip, a Bosnian Serb nationalist.\n- **Complex Alliances**: The assassination set off a chain reaction due to the complex system of alliances in place. Austria-Hungary, with Germany's backing, issued an ultimatum to Serbia. When Serbia did not comply fully, Austria-Hungary declared war on Serbia on July 28, 1914.\n- **Escalation**: This conflict quickly escalated as Russia mobilized to defend Serbia. Germany then declared war on Russia (August 1) and on Russia's ally, France (August 3). Germany's invasion of Belgium on August 4 brought Britain into the war, leading to a widespread conflict involving many nations.\n\n### End of WWI:\n- **Stalemate and Exhaustion**: The war saw trench warfare and a grueling stalemate for much of its duration, particularly on the Western Front. By 1918, the Central Powers (mainly Germany, Austria-Hungary, and the Ottoman Empire) were feeling the strain of prolonged conflict, economic hardship, and military defeats.\n- **American Entry**: The entry of the United States into the war in April 1917 provided a significant boost to the Allies and helped tip the balance against the Central Powers.\n- **Final Offensive and Armistice**: In the summer of 1918, Allied forces launched a series of offensives that pushed back German forces. Facing defeat and internal unrest, Germany sought an end to hostilities.\n- **Armistice**: An armistice was signed on November 11, 1918, at 11 a.m., effectively ending the fighting. This date is now commemorated as Armistice Day or Veterans Day in various countries.\n\n### Aftermath:\nThe formal conclusion of the war came with the signing of the Treaty of Versailles on June 28, 1919, which imposed heavy reparations and territorial losses on Germany and redrew the map of Europe.",
